properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Cape Conran, Marlo.

  • Due to a whale carcass that remains on the beach, there could be an increase in shark activity reported at Point Ricardo.
  • A whale carcass can attract sharks to the area and mean they are closer to the shore than normal.
  • While it is not uncommon for sharks to be present off the Victorian coast, you should exercise additional caution in the area.
  • This is an update, replacing the Advice issued on 23 June.
Avoid the area. Stay informed and do not enter the water at closed beaches.
What you should do:

  • If you see sharks, report the sighting by calling Triple Zero (000) or notify lifesavers immediately if you are at a patrolled beach.
Staying safe at nearby beaches:
  • Always swim, dive or surf with a friend.
  • Swim between the red and yellow flags on patrolled beaches.
  • Don't swim in places where human or animal waste enters the water.
  • Keep away from large schools of fish, seals or other wildlife as these can attract sharks.
Impacts in your area:
  • Victorian Fisheries Authority is assisting wildlife officers and park rangers with the management of the whale carcass.
This message was issued by Victorian Fisheries Authority.

The next update is expected by 07/07/2023 05:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.   
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.location: the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point
properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point.

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOCKER RD BRIDGE AND WANGARATTA.

Minor flooding is occurring along the King River at Docker Rd Bridge and the Ovens River at Wangaratta.
The situation is likely to ease throughout Thursday and Friday.

The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point:

  • Minor flooding is continuing along the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point.
  • The Ovens River at Wangaratta is currently at 11.96 metres and steady, with minor flooding. 
  • The Ovens River at Wangaratta is likely to fell below the minor flood level (11.90 m) overnight Friday into Saturday.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes. 
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
  • Check out the Wangaratta Local Flood Guide for more flood information and what might happen, to help you be best informed and prepared, click here: Wangaratta Local Flood Guide
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.  
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.  Be prepared to act if your situation changes. 
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
Impacts in your area: 

  • Water will be up to Yogi's chin in the Apex Park.
  • Riverside car parks will be closed at Bickerton St, Sydney Beach and Baker St and Apex Park. 
  • Great Alpine Rd is closed at yellow creek.
  • A number of local roads and walking tracks may be closed due to flooding.
  • Parks, hiking tracks and campgrounds are closed due to flooding. To find out more go to www.parkweb.vic.gov.au/safety/flood-affected-parks.
  • Low lying caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded. 
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au. 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/07/2023 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.location: Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham
properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham.

  • Floodwaters from the Murray River tributaries upstream of Barham combined with floodwaters from the local tributaries have caused minor flooding along the Murray River at Barham.
  • The Murray River at Barham is currently at 5.51 metres and rising, above the minor flood level (5.50 metres) The Murray River at Barham may reach around 5.70 metres early next week with minor flooding.
  • The peak forecast at Barham will be provided once upstream peaks have been observed.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions.
What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
Impacts in your area:
  • You may see higher river levels and some minor flooding in areas close to rivers and creeks.
  • Some local roads may be closed or underwater. Do not drive through floodwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 03/07/2023 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge.

MINOR FLOODING CONTINUING AT BANDIANA

No significant rainfall was recorded across the Kiewa River catchment in the 24 hours to 9:00 am Friday. No significant rainfall is forecast for the next few days.

The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge:

Minor flooding is continuing along the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge.

  • The Kiewa River at Bandiana is currently at 2.82 metres and steady, above the minor flood level (2.80 metres). 
  • The Kiewa River at Bandiana may fall below the minor flood level (2.80 m) overnight Friday into Saturday.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
